<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102770264385733></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102770264385733><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102770264385733>Always Tash</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102770264385733#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=175677><span id= >Yelwen</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>2 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jul 26th 1:10 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok here's how it works.&nbsp;&nbsp;Tash line reduces the NPC resistance to magic, we know that.  So it helps the initial casting of any spell take.  With duration spells (DOTs and Mezz and such) the NPC has the chance to resist the spell all over every tick or every time they get hit.  The die is rolled and checked against magic resist, charisma, level, etc. on each opportunity so if you were luck to get a duration spell to stick without tash it may not the second throw or third where with tash it has a much higher chance of not getting resisted. That means that there is a better chance of the Charm lasting the full duration, but it wont make it last longer than that.  Also your group casters are going to be more effective with their dots from your use of tash.  In general ....ALWAYS TASH ... the life you save may be your own ).<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Jul 26 13:01:38 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Yelwen Shapetwister<br>44th Season Enchanter<br>Dragonspawn of the Luclin Server<br><i>"What does not destroy us makes us stronger - what kills us makes us smarter"</i></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102823583328026></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102823583328026><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102823583328026>RE: Always Tash</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102823583328026#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=83141><span id=Scholar>Ellon the Charming</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>28 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 1st 5:17 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.16]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Errr...wrong!<br><br>After level 50, if you tash before the tank gets sufficient aggro, you are one dead Enchanter.<br><br>Use bare mez on incomming adds.&nbsp;&nbsp;If it resists, then you have stuns that can save your bacon.  Once a mob is mezzed, THEN Tash them, so you can keep refreshing mez without having to worry about losing mana to resists.<br><br>Once you hit 54 and get Glamour, you should keep Glamour, Dazzle and Root all memorized.  You Glamour incomming mobs, root them, let Glamour wear off, then re-mez them with Dazzle.  Dazzle is a 96 second mez, while Glamour is 48, but Glamour has a built-in Tash (it's low-resist).<br><br>Take it from a guy who's actually been on the front lines with some real mobs. =D<br><br><br>Ellon 55th level Enchanter.<br>&nbsp;<br>Ellon Silktongue<br>54th level Illusionist<br>Drinal Server<br>Avengers of Honour</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
